antReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>The project seeks to reconceptualise ways of thinking about technology in an extra-European context and to examine the relationship between 'everyday technology' and the transformation of late colonial and early post-colonial societies in South and Southeast Asia. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The research focuses on India and Vietnam, thereby covering both the British and French experience and very different geographical regions. The project aims to question the widespread assumption that it was only 'big technologies' (such as railways and steamships) that really mattered and that, under European direction and control, these had a unique capacity to change non-Western societies. It considers instead the more modest but far-reaching technological changes associated with such innovations as bicycles, sewing-machines and rice-mills which impacted on the lives and livelihoods of millions of people. It will determine how and by whom new technologies were taken up, how far new and old technologies coexisted and how 'everyday technologies' became important cultural goods (for instance, as markers of social status and emblems of modernity). The visual and textual representation of these technologies will form a significant part of the research.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>Research on this project is now complete with respect to both India and Vietnam. Professor Arnold?s research has focused on four innovative technologies - sewing machines, bicycles, rice mills, and typewriters. &lt;/p>

